FAN-fucking-TASTIC RUN!  Set out to run 12, with thoughts of doing 18, but pessimistic about those chances.  Then BOOM!  I'm going 6:30 pace?  This doesn't feel like 6:30 pace... Wow.

Then, 9 miles, 58:30, turn around....do 3 more?  Or do the whole 9 miles out, 9 miles back?  DO IT TO IT.

Start cranking them out, little-to-no fatigue.  Left foot/ankle/calf/leg sort of tensed/cramped up, but I ignored it, it faded after 3 miles.  Things started getting (a little) tough at 15 miles...still cranking out 6:10ishs.

Finished the out and back in 1:54:27...6:30s out with the wind for a generous 9, 6:13s back against it, with rain.  Not bad.  Cooled down with an easy 2 miles.  Could have maintained for probably another 30-45 minutes easily.

(EDIT:  Now that I look back, I ran 20 miles faster before.  However, as I recall, I was pushing it then, and not at all this time.  It was just easy easy easy.  Probably was typing a bit crazy from the 'runners' high' or whatever.)

Set out for a long run....planned to do 19, heading down to the Minnehaha Pkwy paths via Calhoun and Harriet.  Felt good....strongish wind for the first 5 miles, but not bad..it became a more gentle breeze by the time I was headed East.

Finally hit my stride around 7 miles...probably around 6:35-6:30s, feeling good, but not tooo good, so I held back when my legs naturally tried to pick it up.

Once I hit the River Pkwy, it was go time.  I started picking it up more and more felt good, then great, and then the shirt came off (I was heating up)...I was hoping I wouldn't hit the wall when I got to the Greenway.

I didn't.  Turned onto the Greenway and started breaking it down.  My leg (Sartorius) stiffened up for a mile, but it disappeared.  If there was a biker that wasn't wearing spandex, I passed them.  I got a honk from Mark Forsberg as I passed under Hiawatha Ave, since the bridge is closed.  I finished the last 3 miles in 16:30, the last mile in a little under 5:30.  SOLID SOLID SOLID.

I ran 19 miles in 1:57:31, averaging 6:11 per mile.  I definitely finished the last 10 in under an hour...probably faster than 5:50 pace.

All that said, I did put forth some effort over the last 4 miles...it felt pretty relaxed, and the last mile was a breeze.  My stride lengthened and got really smooth, despite some lactic in my upper body.  ....I should really sign up for a race..

I decided at that point that I should PROBABLY cool down for a little bit.  So I made it an even 20, with a shakeout mile.
Easy, beautiful shakeout.  Thought I might do my longer run for the day, but I was still very stiff at 4 miles.

The 1' intervals all rolled along really well, and the last 2 were super fast.  I felt really good despite 20 on Saturday and a double yesterday.

Back tracking, I covered about 8.5 miles for the workout, 2.5 of which was rest in between.  30 minutes for about 6 miles, probably just a little under.

EDIT:

I covered more like 8.25 miles... but the rest (17') was likely slower than 7' pace... Even at 2.5 miles of rest I was 5:12 / mile.

WHOA. Crazy day for a race. Temps around 0F all day, 20 mph winds (though protected for 95% of the course. Waxed with SkiGo 380 powder wax, SkiGo C110 fluoro powder. Skis were NOT fast, but not slow compared to others. Got a little pick up on downhills and seemed to be a little faster than others there too. Kick wax was Rex ProGrip Green covered with Swix VR30. Kick was sticky. Anders and I got a final coat of Toko X-Cold at the start which helped for the first 10-15k. The tracks were mostly snow-filled. The group did not want to break trail in the tracks--a lot of skiing outside the tracks making stability and having good form tough, especially for me. The hills were brutally slow and the leaders of the chase pack seemed to slow-herringbone the hills (tactically). I moved to the front of the chase pack (2 others far ahead) and pulled for 2k or so somewhere between 10-20k...I should not have made this effort, ended up falling back after a ways. Slowed down, focused on technique and recovered. Started gaining ground after the half-way point, and felt better. My kick was still icing up and I had to kick it off every time I went up a hill / skied outside the tracks. Moved up well from the 35-40k--after being 15th at the half-way point. Passed Anders and two others with 5k to go and put a little gap--but no tracks and rough uneven terrain slowed me down and they caught up. The two others passed me with 1k to go (whiteout conditions near the dome) and I had a pretty good finish.

Overall, a GREAT race, but I can race better/smarter/harder next time I think. 10th place finish was a surprise and a treat! What a great race.

WHOA! Great conditions. Well-groomed but soft track over a hard base. Despite conditions around 0F again, my skis were rockets and Pojke pulled. Pojke was SOOO excited to get going and pulled harder than he ever has before. We blasted down the first 9k. I overtook Pojke on the hills a couple times, but he was unfazed. He pooped with 2k to go--which was my fault for not taking him for a longer walk in the morning--to make sure he pooped twice. The last 2k were tough as Pojke tired, but he gained some energy to over-take a 2 dog team. The slow flat conditions near the stadium were tough but we finished strong. Won by over 7:30 in the 1 dog category and were only 90s behind the 2 dog team over 12k. Boom!

Almanzo 100 mile gravel bike race in Southern MN.  Felt pretty chipper for the first 30 miles.  Started to slow after that.  Bike was performing flawlessly.  Some farmers tried to stop us from taking a road due to doing their ammonia fertilizer treatment...but we kept going.

At around 40 or 50 miles in, I started to falter, and my breathing became more and more shallow--perhaps a reaction to all the dust?  Or the short bout of breathing in some ammonia?  I'm not sure, but it was a sufferfest after that.  Luckily, I had Anders' wheel to follow ahead of me, or the race would have been much longer.

Some clutch food / water stops at 70 miles, and later at around 80 miles.  Thanks to Banjo Brothers for Nutter Butters and Coke.  Damn that was good.

Breathing got worse all the way to the end...it took a good 30 minutes to get to a point where I was no longer anxious and another hour to get back to near normal.  Anders brought me some Brompheniramine which may have helped...not sure.

I will definitely do this race again, but I will definitely need to do more riding before.

Hmmm.  This run was a bit disconcerting.  Started out in the morning during a light drizzle (the main storm had already passed).  The first miles were a bit slow--warming up the legs.  Quickly found my stride and felt good.  Headed toward Minnehaha PKWY trail for the typical 19 mi. long loop.  Sometime around 8-10 miles in I started feeling a pain in the front of my lower right leg (about 4-6 inches up from my ankle).  I grew more and more nervous as the run went on the and the pain continued to get worse (which I perceived to be muscular--since the pain intensified as I picked up my foot).  I stopped briefly twice to see if I could quickly stretch out the pain ('knot'?) but to no avail.  The last 2 or 3 miles probably could have been faster--as I was feeling good--but the pain prevented me from really locking it down.  I slowed down after 17 miles and then walked the last half mile.  The pain continued in force for the next 2-3 hours, but then diminished in the afternoon.  No pain the next day.  Very strange--I was worried about a stress fracture...less so now.

A damn good race.

Despite my lack of confidence a week out, I pulled things together the last few days before the race and got my head in the right place.  I was confident that I could hit 5:15 miles, no problem.  Felt great when I woke up, and once I got to the course my legs were ready to rock.

48F and misting the whole time.  Great for the start.  Nick Ross and I got out at 5:18 pace for the first 4 miles...which was slower than I wanted, but I felt very relaxed and was able to just roll with our group.  After about 5 miles the group faltered a little so I moved to the front and pushed ahead a little.  I didn't really look back for 2 miles, but it turned out I had gapped them.

Ran by myself for the rest of the race.  I should have latched on to a TCTC runner as he went by, but I lost focus for just long enough that he had gapped me as well.  Still felt strong as I came into town.  Rolled down the brick-covered Superior Street without any issues.  But again, as in 2012, the turns in the last mile really took their toll.  Mental fatigue had set in and it was tough to navigate all the twists and turns.  Ended up getting passed by 4 runners near the finish, but still came through strong.

I was quite chilled over the last couple miles.  I may not have had enough to eat the day before...but my energy stores were fine for running.  Luckily I got my clothes on fairly quickly and cooled down with John Leaf...the last half mile I slowed to near 10 minute pace..my energy had completely depleted.  Loaded up on snacks and went back to the hotel to get a shower.

All-in-all, a great effort.  Unfortunately, a slower start and racing alone made it tough to meet a goal of 68:XX.  I only felt like I was really going to the well over the last 1.5 miles, and that was mostly from mental fatigue, my legs were still working fine.  It give me a lot of confidence for the next long race I have.

The rain started soon after and quickly built into a downpour.  The streets were flooding and it was absolutely glorious.  I was inspired to write a silly poem:

It's going to rain--

06:27

Moving
over the asphalt.
Shoes taking the lead
one after the other.

Sliding
in from the West,
the wind storms in--
cool, soft.

06:22

Churning
wind through the leaves--
water on the lake.
--as it flow around my feet.

Flowing
through the streets.
Feet hard on the path
feel the water
over and between my toes.

6:13

Pounding
in my chest
and onto my head.
Onto my arms
onto the pavement.

Gushing
in my arteries
in the gutter
into the storm drain

5:59

Rolling
down my face,
over my lips,
into my mouth.
Each movement is smooth--
sliding, frictionless

Dancing
in the pools,
each step
in between the drops.

5:47

It's going to rain--
I'm going to run.

10 hours of sleep on Friday night, nap in the afternoon on Saturday.  Spaghetti at 1p, PBJ at 5p, 6 hours of sleep on Saturday night.  ProBar in the morning with 20oz of coffee.  Nice.  Feeling good.  Feeling light and race-y.

Warmed up with Tim Lillehaugen at the start--did about 18 minutes, then added on a good number of strides and shakeout stuffs.  37F, no wind.  Half tights, singlet, arm sleeves, perfect.

The race went out REALLY fast, but then tapered down to a just fast pace after 200m of getting it out of our systems.  Settled in the with chase group and relaxed through the first 4 miles.  Stepped off a bit on the uphills and let fly a little on the downhills--which worked out well I think.  Everything went way better than I expected.  I rolled through the hills really well on River Road and had plenty of energy going up Summit.  I felt smooth, and strong throughout, and really only faltered when I didn't have someone to run with after the halfway point.  I should have toughened up for a mile and stuck with the group.  It turns out the race was .14 miles short--due to the lead police vehicle not making a proper turn.  Oh well--52:05 would be 52:49ish--which is still A OK by me.

150+ minute classic ski at Hyland.  WHOA.  Grooming overnight and the 5k loop is a fucking winter wonderland.  Solid classic track--washed out only on the downhills.  Fast skate deck.  Rex ProGrip Blue was just solid enough to give just the right amount of kick for practicing my technique.  Feeling a lot better and this much skiing is giving me some huge confidence.
Super easy shakeout run with the pup.  Feeling good despite 8+ hours of activity over the last 3 days. Pojke loved it too!
A slow start on a cold day.  Being tired will do that too.  Finally was feeling good by the end of the run.  Beautiful and sunny
9 from work.  Frigid, but OK.  Slow.  Maybe I'm overtraining.

Evening classic ski at Elm Creek with Amy.  Went slow with her the whole time.  Subzero conditions and squeaky snow means SWIX POLAR kick wax.  My favorite.  Bomber kick and good glide (considering).  Love it.

Out from work early means a ski at Hyland.  Not sure how many laps I did...but maybe 5?  6?  5 1/2?  Who knows.  I forgot the GPS.  Didn't feel so hot, but it was good to get out on the show.  NYE party with Amy afterwards.

130 minute skate ski at Hyland. Warmed up for 30 minutes then did some fast efforts. it was supposed to be 8 x 3' with 1' rest, but my shirt sleeve activated the 'lap' button when I was pulling it up my arm. So there were probably 2 short efforts in the first 4. I did an extra interval at the end to compensate.

Good efforts. Next time I need to really focus on good technique--and then move up to stronger efforts from there.

Finished with another hour of easy skiing. Good. I need more sleep for this shirt.
Easy run with the pup...!!

Easy run from work. Feeling pretty good despite all the efforts this week. I'll be at 16 hours of running/skiing for the last 7 days after my workout tonight. Holy Shit. I also need new shoes soon....

An easy classic ski at Elm Creek. SkiGo HF Blue was finally kicking--albeit not very well. My technique has certainly gotten a lot better as I would have been very frustrated and slipping frequently if I had kick this bad earlier in the season. Definitely getting much better and nailing my kick every time--though fatigue still makes me a little sloppy. Kept my heart rate at 162 BPM average--so at level 2 (ish). Good.

Whoa. Cold. Something like -4F for the start. That's nuts.

Short warm up, and then I put on my race gloves--a little too long in the cold because they didn't warm up completely during the next 26 minutes.

I fell in the first 200m--which was dumb. Just caught an edge and tipped over. Made up the ground pretty quickly--my skis were feeling pretty darn fast. Didn't quite make it to the front group who finished 2-3 minutes ahead of me. Part of me thinks I could have hung on to them, but I'm not sure.

Felt good through 7.5k, but my last lap was certainly sloppy. I should have just tucked in behind someone in the chase pack and drafted until the final hill....but I'm not smart at racing skiing 10ks. Oh well.

Skis slowed by the end too--I guess I need to get better at corking fluoro applications.

Finished 8 out of 42. 3 out of 8 for 19-29 year olds.

Another daily 9 miles from work. Cold --hovering below 0F. Felt good nonetheless--probably more than I should after yesterday's race...but that's a good thing. Yesterday's race was less effort than I've done in the last 6 days anyway...

Oof. Not a great race. I felt tired soon after the gun and while my skis were fast at the start--they slowed down dramatically after about 10k. Fell once while trying to pass someone on a narrow trail and lost the pack. Fell again at the bottom of a fast turn after a hill. Started hitting the wall with about 8k to go...but thought it was shorter so I didn't take an energy gel. Struggled to the finish.

I'm glad it was a shorter race, and maybe this is a good learning lesson for future races. Take more gels--don't pass when it's narrow. I think my training will pay off eventually...just not right now.

It was single digits at the start, but warmed up fast--the sun was quite steamy!

From work. Good. Felt quick.
20 minute skijor with POjke. Too much to do to add on at Wirth.

Classic ski at Wirth. Testing out the two pairs of Atomic WC Classic Skis. The original SDS ended up winning--but they were comparable in all sections with the exception of the down hill. The SDS was faster.

By feel, I think the SDS was faster as well, and had slightly better grip.

Went skijoring with Pojke on the lakes for 20 minutes too!
Gettin' primed for the race. 7 miles easy. 6 pick ups from 45 to 30 seconds apiece. Feeling pretty good.
Easy shakeout with the pup before leaving for the U.P.

Tough Race. Anders and I arrived 1:45 before our race start to test kick wax. KR50 was good, VR55 was just as good, but a little less sticky. Covered with Start FHF40, both were still good, but VR55 was just a little better. Testing the skis was our warmup, but occurred a little too far away from the race start to be effective. I guess corking in the kick wax was our warm up. Barely made it to the line, and was 4 people back from the start. We need to remember to put some test/warmup skis in the tracks well before the start.

Anders was with the lead pack from the start, I struggled to get a good start and the pack disappeared, never to be seen again.

The first 12k was rough--striding was not working well for me, and having no one to follow was not making it easier. The next 12k was even worse, with some fresh snow, my skis were icing, and I was running up most of the hills, feeling sorry for myself.

Finally started feeling just OK after the halfway point and some nice long downhills, but still had no one to ski with. The third quarter was skied out of the tracks the whole time--since the tracks were slow and no one wanted to be the first to ski in them.

FINALLY felt good during the last 5k or so, after some icy hills, and dirty sections of the course. Double poling felt strong...but it was too late to make much of a difference.

Saw Anders 50m ahead of me just as we entered the stadium. I guess the race turned out OK, but I'm frustrated by the fact that I never really felt good throughout the whole race.

Tough waxing conditions, but no one was going to nail kick wax for the whole race, considering the falling snow, and micro-climates everywhere. I need to work on my striding more in the early season to be ready for this race next year.

Whoa! Fast skijor with Pojke. Got there right before the start, Pojke freaked out (as usual) and then pulled hard for 10k. The last 4 was a bit of a struggle, but we made it. did a 10:11 5k somewhere in the middle, and had good control and fairly fast skis on the 1' of powder that was over a hard-packed skate deck. A lot of fun, and Pojke was tired.
A good effort from work. Felt relaxed, and my muscles loosened up considerably by the end. Beautiful 40F+ day...but the snow is all but gone.

Skate skiing workout at Elm Creek. Warmed up fro 45 minutes then did the 2.4k loop hard with 2 minutes rest. Was only planning on 4, but decided to do a fifth. My form was great through the fourth effort, but I got sloppy on the fifth. Definitely feeling much stronger, and my balance on the uneven soft snow as still pretty good. Great effort all around.

Couldn't get myself to do two more laps on the hamster wheel, so 108 minutes will have to do.
Started off slow and creaky, but warmed up well. Felt pretty good.
Easy run with the pup to give him some exercise!
Skate ski at Wirth. 4'+ of sugar over ice. It made the tough snow making loop even tougher. Oh well. Got in almost an hour.
Nice run. A little tired...but still good.
Went to Elm Creek, but was too tired to do more than 50 minutes of skiing. Blah. Windy too.
7 miles from work. Sunny. Got some exercise. Fine.
Easy run with Anders and the pup to pick up my registration. Good run. Nice shakeout for the pup.

FUCK. Amy went to get Pojke, but could not find my car. I should have done it myself. I was late to the race (who knows how late) and ended up taking 4th. Recovered well, but fell a couple times which didn't help. SHIT.
Warm Up.

Whoa! Fast day. Pojke pulled SUPER hard. Got out pretty well...wasn't as quick as I could have been up the first long hill, but it was OK. Blasted down the sledding hill and gapped the competition going back up. Pojke was still pulling, but couldn't keep up with the 2 dog team ahead of us. Fell, but recovered quickly on the 180 turn adjacent to the upper stadium. Pojke DOMINATED the rest of the race. Never slowed, and killed it even though my skis were rockets. Put 1:32 on the next team of 2 dogs, and 2:00 on the winner from the first day to win the 2-day event. BOOM.

Holy shit. 3:14 per mile on that hilly course. Sexy. 2:01 / kilo is sick too.
Skate ski with Anders at Theo Wirth. Conditions were fast and fun. Did two laps of double poling which was tough...Anders is the premo double-poler and gave me a few tips. Great ski! Cold hands!
Good run. Felt Ok.

Easy run with the pup during the boil of brewing. Let him off leash on Cedar Lake Pkwy / Kenilworth. It was fun to watch him run faster than 6' pace straight through the woods next to me. 1-2' of powder on the trail was nice.
A nice run. A little underdressed. Optimistic about the sun, but didn't consider the wind. OK.
Skate ski at Wirth. OK. Felt a little tired, but still good. Cold, so only managed 60 minutes.
Good. Quick in the end. Sunny!
Skijor with Pojke. Ice and drifting snow on Cedar Lake made it short and scary.
7 miles from work. Sunny, and fairly warm. Felt good. I did 6x 20' strides. Good.

Hmmm... 7th is good, but I should have done better. I was at the tail of the lead pack after the first lap, but then the guy ahead of me let a gap form, and I waited too long to get around him. I couldn't make up the ground, and couldn't get back onto the train. Oh well.

My poling was strong throughout, and I definitely could have held on if I had the draft. I might not have placed, better, but would have been more pleased with my race effort.
Easy run with the pup during brewing.  5 miles, slowish, but good.
SLOW conditions at Hyland.  I had to V2 the downhills.  Good ski though, focused on technique a little.  Trying to engage both my abs and legs an equal amount when skating.

WHOA.  SUPER fun race.  3 team race for the first lap.  Sierra/Lexi took the lead but Pojke and I soon moved up next to them.  Sierra's dog was a little unwieldy and was getting in our way.  Eventually I settled behind Sierra, Dallas/Comet close behind.

Made a move to take the lead at the lap mark, but again, couldn't quite get around.  Pojke started to eat snow while running, making me a little worried/frustrated.  Sierra/Lexi gapped us by ~40m.  Over the last km, I started to put in a finishing sprint effort, and Pojke caught on, pulling hard!  We took a sick inside line around the 180 corner with 500m to go and started to pull ahead.  Neck and neck on the 200m homestraight--we were staring to pull ahead a little.  Then Lexi started heading left to lap again, so Pojke and I had our break and won!

SUPER fast out there, and fun to race so close for the entire race.  Pojke pulled harder at the Sunday City of Lakes, but today was a great effort all around.  So much fun to see the dogs go crazy over racing.

Dalahorse--awesome.

Ski with Anders at Theo Wirth.  Nice conditions, warm, and still light outside.  Did 5x 40-45 second efforts up the sledding hill, 60' rest on the way down.  A very hard effort, it was good.  Maybe I should do more.
Good.  Snowy, a little slick.  Hungry/thirsty, but ended well
At Wirth with Nick.  Did some 3' intervals, but stopped after 7 due to cold and icy conditions making it difficult to really make a strong effort.  Hands nearly froze in the below zero wind chill.
Good run from work.  Felt great.  Cold, but not windy.  Getting pumped for the Birkie--I think my training is starting to accumulate into a high fitness level.
Whoa.  Good.  Felt good and then just dropped a couple 6:20 miles at the end--not too much effort.  I'm finally feeling good.  Good news for next weekend.
Cold and Windy.  Amy and I drove to Lake Maria State Park and spent a night in one of the cabins.  It included about 3 miles of hiking for fun.  Good day off before the Birkie.
Another off day--hiking at Lake Maria, plus with Pojke in Eloise Butler.  Probably 5 miles all together.  Good, relaxing efforts.

Skate ski at Wirth with Anders.  60 minutes.  A couple race efforts (not really worth mentioning).  Not feeling too hot, felt a little uncomfortable on skis after 4 days off.  I'll be fine though.  Some workouts this week will settle that.

Skate ski at Elm Creek.  Cold and windy.  Nevertheless, I dressed perfectly and got in a decent workout.

10x 2' on 1' off.  Accidentally did one 3' on around number 7.  Whoops.  Good effort and feeling pretty fast throughout.  Maybe went a little hard in the middle but evened it out at the end.  Good efforts.  Ready for the Birkie.
Cold, windy.  Braved -20F windchills from work.  Nothing fast, but felt everywhere from great to sluggish.  2 more days to feel awesome.  Ready for that top 50 finish.
A relaxed effort.  Did 8x 30-40' surges/strides during the run--rest was as I felt.  Feeling pretty good.  Need to focus my mind on the goal.
Easy shakeout with the pup.  Didn't really feel all that great at all...but some rest tonight and I'll be primed for 51k of skiing.

A good race but not a great race.  Felt pretty relaxed on the warm up, skis felt slippery.  Not glassy, but good.  The first 8k went by easily, and I was in a good pack.  I was skiing by myself for the next 8k--keeping up only 40m behind the next group.  Finally caught up and skied with Anders and others for a while.  Gels were taken at good moments--got water quickly and easily.  However, come 14k to go, when I was hoping to make some efforts to increase the pace, the energy wasn't there.  10k to go, Anders and others broke away.  I had a clutch 1/2 bottle of gatorade with 6k to go, but it wasn't enough to wake me from the dead.  Got pulled 2/3rds of the way across the lake, but didn't have much to give a hard effort for the final kilometer.

All in all, a good effort, but definitely felt like I was lacking something.  Lack of energy seemed to be holding me back--and it seemed to be partially my CV.  My strength was there, and fatigue was not setting in, I just didn't have gas in the tank.  I'm pleased to finish higher than last year, but I think I can do better.
Could have / should have run.  I was not too fatigued from the Birkie...but I was a little hung over and tired from lack of sleep.  Oh well.
Good.  Felt fine.
Run with the pup.  Too angry/depressed/sleep-deprived to do anything more.  Fuck.
Felt fine.  Still a little pissed.  Spring Fever?
Classic ski at Wirth.  First one since the Noque.  Felt really good actually.  Good striding efforts on the hills.  Cold, but not too cold.
Classic ski at Wirth.  Was only going to do a little bit...almost didn't do any.  But it was a good effort.
From Work.
Post happy hour run with Anders.  Felt a little tipsy for the start--maybe.  Ready to have a good weekend though.
Off. Boring.
Skate ski at Wirth.  Tired and stupid.
Off.  Boring.
Ski (classic and skate) at Wirth with Anders.  Practicing transitions for the Skiathlon at the Great Bear Chase.  I need to get my Combi boots back from Frankie..!
Snowy, but good.  Felt fine.
Ugh.  Not a fantastic run.  HR seemed to be spiking despite an easy effort.  Maybe it's just the cold.
3 mile warm up.  8x 1' on 1' off.  Hovered at ~5:15 pace.  Felt good.  Added 3 x 30' finishing pace.  Good tune up.  Going to KILL it in Calumet.
Easy shakeout in the morning with the pup.  OK.

Tough race.  Slow conditions throughout, and slow skis.

Classic race went out in a pack of ~10.  Stayed together until the last 5k or so of the first lap.  My skis were actually pretty fast, but I started getting fatigued and the top field gapped me (and Anders).  We caught one guy, but that was it.  My technique was still very good, but slowing skis did not help in the last bit.

Transition went pretty good.  I was a little out of it, and didn't have my skate skis in a good position to slide in next to them.  Didn't lose much time though.  Good.

Skate was a little rough at the start, and slow skis made it even tougher.  It seemed that despite having a good ski for the conditions, the wax just made climbing terrible.  I couldn't and didn't catch anyone, and just barely didn't let anyone catch me.  My technique was good through the first 15k, but I was just about beat for the last 10k.  Skiing around lots of other racers made it tough too.  It was a good effort, but the slow conditions tired me early.

It was a good race, and since the two 20-24ers were in the top four, I won a wooden ski!
A beautiful day, but I needed some time off.

Beautiful run with the pup around the lakes.  Shorts and a shirt was just a little warm.  Couldn't ask for more.

However, soon after I completed my run, my achilles started to feel TERRIBLE.  Very painful.  Damn it.

Windy.  Very windy.  Legs are still fatigued from getting back into things.  Achilles started to get painful at the end.

Did a 5 mile tempo on a whim.  It went pretty good.  I think I'm in OK shape, but not spectacular.  Definitely on a good level. Miles were 5:33, 5:45, 5:38, 5:49, 5:39.  The 4th one had wind and a hill.

Good effort and felt pretty relaxed considering it was the first uptempo effort in a month.
A good run.  Quick.  Dropped some sub 6:30s.
OK.  Ran to Bogart's Donuts, ate a Vanilla Cream-filled doozy, ran back.  Beautiful sunny morning.
Did some biking on the newly-cleaned Focus.  17ish miles.  It was a blast.
MOAR biking.  This time, shredding some single track on the Kona with the freshly tuned brakes (and new lever).  Hot damn, that dirt feels good.

Ugh.  Rough day (sort of).

Felt great at the start...and clearly went out way too fast.  However, settling back into the 5:20s was just fine.  Felt smooth for the most part.  After 4 miles, I started losing it a little, but not too badly.

Then, in the last 1200, I received a sharp, stabbing pain in my abs.  It hurt worse than anything else I've experienced.  Not a side ache.  Dreadful finish.

Oh well.  Not bad, all things considered.
an hour of mountain biking with Anders.  Fun.  Love it.

Long Run?  Good.  Felt awesome for the entirety of it.  Broke it down a little at the end, but generally was just enjoying the sun, and farmscape in Iowa.  Amy rode with me.  A good day.  Pojke was beat!
Foot pads are sore?  OK.

Went to Elm Creek for some singletrack.  Took the Focus.  SUPER fun.  All the trails took an hour to ride, start to finish.  Hit a couple features, but was a little scared of the others--I'll have to get some confidence.  The prairie riding was fast and fun to shred.

Did 4.  Whatever.  OK.

Long run.  Got it done before 10a.  NBD.

Felt good.  Slow start, but broke it down OK at the end.  Nothing sub 6, but I felt relaxed.  Pojke was feeling good too--especially after he took a dip in Isles at mile 15.

6:45 pace, maybe a little faster.  Meh.
60 minutes of Singletrack at Lebanon Hills with Amy.  Fun stuff.  No crashing.  I need to go back and shred some of the features.
Relaxed run with Anders and the pup.  Rainy--felt good.  Did some strides/intervals (300m).  Felt good.  Maybe the TC 1 Mile race won't be awful.
From work.  Nice afternoon.
Night singletrack at Wirth with bright lamps.  With Anders.  Not fast, but super fun.  Good to get out, and a beautiful, cool night.

Not a bad effort.  A bit of a headwind kept the splits in check throughout.

5:41, 5:49, 5:48, 6:00 (uphill), 5:47, 5:34 (downhill).

Stopped by the par 3 clubhouse (shack?) because of a bowel emergency.  The man at the counter yelled at me for not wearing a shirt while chasing me to the bathroom and throwing rolls of TP.  Granted, maybe I shouldn't feel entitled to use any nearby toilet while running, but what's a guy to do when the pressure is on and no Porta-Pottys in sight?

Finshed with some 30' strides and a long cool down.  Finished just before the rain started.

Felt fine.  Humid.  But nice.
